{
  "texts": [
    "4 Interestingly, the AI Act explicitly adopts a risk-based approach, that groups together AI systems into different levels of risk.",
    "In particular, it explicitly distinguishes systems involving unacceptable risks (e.g., those used for social scoring) and high-risk systems (e.g., those used for predictive justice).",
    "Two other levels of risk can be identified, even if no precise label is employed in the AI Act: limited-risk systems (e.g., chatbots) and minimal-risk systems (e.g., spam filters).",
    "Each level of risk is then associated with a specific level of regulation: unacceptably risky systems are prohibited (Art.",
    "5); high-risk systems need to comply with strict requirements concerning, among other things, traceability, human oversight, accuracy, security, and robustness (Chapter III); limited-risk systems must respect transparency requirements (Art. 50);"
  ]
}